\begin_body

\begin_layout Standard
Group foraging model.
 We have a single well-mixed population,
 in which individuals can choose to join a group or to forage alone.
 Individuals encounter 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 patches in each time step,
 in which 
\begin_inset Formula $k\sim\mathrm{Pois}(\lambda)$
\end_inset

,
 similar to existing models of group foraging 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citep
key "Caraco1981,Clark1986"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 and have a handling time of 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

.
 Crucially,
 individuals can vary in their encounter rate 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda$
\end_inset

 and their handling time,
 dependent on their quality (or more interestingly,
 dependent on their current level of resources,
 even),
 however individuals lack any knowledge about their own quality or that of their group mates.
 Yet,
 individuals can learn via various proxies,
 namely how well larvae develop.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Individuals are characterised by two state variables,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 Here,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 is the cumulative amount of food provided to the larvae at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

,
 while 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 is an individual's quality as a forager,
 where individuals of higher 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

 have a higher success as a forager than individuals of lower 
\begin_inset Formula $y$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Individuals can either decide to stay on their own during breeding or pair up with another,
 randomly chosen individual.
 Hence,
 we have two different fitnesses,
 namely 
\begin_inset Formula $W(x,t,T)$
\end_inset

 for those individuals who stay together and 
\begin_inset Formula $V(x,t,T)$
\end_inset

 for those individuals who remain alone.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Terminal fitness
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The terminal fitness function 
\begin_inset Formula $W\left(x,t,T\right)$
\end_inset

,
 which reflects survival and fecundity during the penultimate time step 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 to the final time step 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

.
 We assume that terminal fitness is a decelerating function of the amount of resources an individual / group ?
 has gathered.
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W\left(x(t),t,T\right) & =1-e^{-k\left(x(t)-x_{\mathrm{min}}\right)},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{\mathrm{min}}$
\end_inset

 is the minimum amount of food needed to warrant survival of at least some of the brood.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
can either decide to raise a nest alone or they can decide to pair up with another individual.
 They have t
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Food encounters
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Similar to 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Mangel1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 we assume that a group of size 
\begin_inset Formula $n$
\end_inset

 (where 
\begin_inset Formula $n\in1,2$
\end_inset

) has an encounter probability of food that is
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
\lambda\left(y_{1}+y_{2}\right) & =1-e^{-\varepsilon\left(y_{1}+y_{2}\right)},
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon$
\end_inset

 reflects the area covered per unit time multiplied by the density of the food items and 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{i}$
\end_inset

 reflects foraging quality.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Larval state
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If no food is found during a time step,
 the larval state is reduced by a fixed amount of 
\begin_inset Formula $a_{\mathrm{c}}$
\end_inset

 (we could vary this,
 e.g.,
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Mangel1990"
literal "false"

\end_inset

 eq.
 [3] allows for both a fixed and relative amount),
 reflecing that larvae invest a certain amount of energy for basic physiological function.
 In case individuals find resources 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
x^{\prime}(t+1) & =x(t)-a_{\mathrm{c}}+R/n,
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 is the value of the resources that have been recovered by 
\begin_inset Formula $0\leq n_{\mathrm{f}}(t)\leq2$
\end_inset

 individuals that have been foraging at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Actions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
During each time step,
 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $f(y,x(t))$
\end_inset

 an individual decides to go foraging,
 while it stays at home with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $1-f(y,x(t))$
\end_inset

.
 If an individual goes out to forage it may get predated upon with rate 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\mathrm{f}}$
\end_inset

.
 If an individual leaves the home patch,
 it also risks that the nest gets predated,
 with probability 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\mathrm{h}}\left(n(t)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Because nest defense may be essential to the survival of the brood,
 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\mathrm{h}}(n(t))$
\end_inset

 increases with increasing numbers of individuals 
\begin_inset Formula $n(t)$
\end_inset

 out foraging.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Upon predation of the nest we assume that fitness until the end of the season
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
The dynamic programming equation
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consequently,
 we then have the fitness of an individual of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{1}$
\end_inset

 together with another individual of quality 
\begin_inset Formula $y_{2}$
\end_inset

 .
 We have seven events that can happen,
 which we number here as 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{1}\left(x\left(t\right),t\right)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $W_{7}\left(x\left(t\right),t\right)$
\end_inset

,
 where
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W\left(x(t),t\right) & =\sum^{7}_{i=1}W_{i}\left(x(t),t\right).
\end{align*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Event 1:
 both individuals forage and return
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We have
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W_{1}\left(x\left(t\right),t\right) & =f\left(y_{1},x(t)\right)f\left(y_{2},x(t)\right)\left(1-p_{\mathrm{f}}\right)^{2}\left(1-p_{h}\left(0\right)\right)\left[\lambda\left(y_{1}+y_{2}\right)W\left(x^{\prime}\left(t+1\right),t+1\right)+\left(1-\lambda\left(y_{1}+y_{2}\right)\right)W\left(x^{\prime\prime}\left(t+1\right),t+1\right)\right],
\end{align*}

\end_inset

notice that when the nest would get predated during foraging,
 we assume that fitness is 
\begin_inset Formula $0$
\end_inset

 (although this assumption can be changed later on).
 The part between straight brackets reflects that individuals can either find food,
 in which case fitness is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $W(x^{\prime}(t+1),t+1)$
\end_inset

 or they do not find food,
 in which case fitness is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $W\left(x^{\prime\prime}\left(t+1\right),t+1\right)$
\end_inset

.
 Here,
 
\begin_inset Formula $x^{\prime}(t+1)$
\end_inset

 is the amount of resources provided to larvae in case indiivdual
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Event 2:
 both individuals forage,
 one dies
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Once the focal has died,
 the focal will still obtain fitness through offspring that the non-focal will still care for.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align*}
W_{2}\left(x\left(t\right),t\right) & =f\left(y_{1},x(t)\right)f\left(y_{2},x(t)\right)p_{\mathrm{f}}\left(1-p_{\mathrm{f}}\right)\left(1-p_{h}\left(0\right)\right)\frac{1}{2}\left[\lambda\left(y_{1}\right)V\left(x^{\prime}\left(t+1\right),t+1\right)+\left(1-\lambda\left(y_{1}\right)\right)V\left(x^{\prime\prime}\left(t+1\right),t+1\right)\right.\\
 & +\left.\lambda\left(y_{2}\right)U\left(x^{\prime}\left(t+1\right),t+1\right)+\left(1-\lambda\left(y_{2}\right)\right)U\left(x^{\prime\prime}\left(t+1\right),t+1\right)\right],
\end{align*}

\end_inset

where as individuals are now alone the focal's fitness is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $V(x^{\prime}(t+1),t+1)$
\end_inset

 as the focal is now a lone breeder.
 If the focal does not survive fitness is given by 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

.
 
